PART 3: ПЂ AS PERIODICITY вЂ” THE CIRCLE IN WALSH SPACE
======================================================================

  In continuous Fourier analysis: e^{i2ПЂft} has period 1/f.
  In Walsh-Fourier analysis over F_2: the "period" is always 2.
  Every Walsh function w_S(x) = (-1)^{<S,x>} satisfies w_SВІ = 1.

  So: 2ПЂ in Fourier в†” 2 in Walsh. The circle SВ№ collapses to Z/2.

  But ПЂ STILL appears: the continuous Fourier transform of H
  (viewed as function on {0,1}^m вЉ‚ R^m) has ПЂ in the kernel.

  More deeply: the EIGENVALUES of the adjacency matrix A of a
  tournament contain cos(2ПЂk/n) for circulant tournaments.
  For the cyclic tournament C_n: eigenvalues = ОЈ П‰^{jk} for QR j.

  For C_5: eigenvalues involve cos(2ПЂ/5) = (в€љ5-1)/4 = (П„-1)/2.
  So ПЂ and П„ are LINKED through the regular pentagon:
    cos(2ПЂ/5) = (П„-1)/2 = 1/(2П„)
    cos(ПЂ/5) = П„/2

  The pentagon is the geometric nexus where ПЂ meets П„ meets 5.

