PART 9: VITALI ATOMS вЂ” THE UNMEASURABLE INTERIOR OF H-FIBERS
======================================================================

  The Vitali set demonstrates: not all subsets of [0,1] are measurable.
  The key: translation-invariance + countable additivity в†’ contradiction.

  In tournament theory, the "measure" is the UNIFORM distribution
  on 2^m tournaments. Every subset IS measurable (finite set).
  But the ALGEBRAIC STRUCTURE imposes a different notion:

  H-MEASURABLE: a property is H-measurable if it's constant on H-fibers.
  (H,cв‚ѓ)-MEASURABLE: constant on (H,cв‚ѓ)-fibers.
  DUALITY-MEASURABLE: invariant under all (Z/2)^4 dualities.

  The VITALI PHENOMENON: some tournament properties are NOT
  H-measurable. Within a fiber HвЃ»В№(h), tournaments differ in
  ways invisible to H. These differences are the "Vitali atoms."

  At n=5, H=15 has TWO types:
  - 40 tournaments with I(О©,x) = 1+5x  (cв‚ѓ=4, cв‚…=1)
  - 24 tournaments with I(О©,x) = 1+6x  (cв‚ѓ=5, cв‚…=1)
  These are distinguishable by cв‚ѓ but NOT by H.

  The hierarchy of measurability:
    H-measurable вЉ‚ (H,cв‚ѓ)-measurable вЉ‚ О©-measurable вЉ‚ score-measurable вЉ‚ full

  Each level reveals more "atoms" within the previous level's fibers.
  The "non-measurable" part = what NO polynomial number of invariants captures.

  Vitali atom decomposition at n=5:
  (What H cannot see within its fibers)
    H=3: 3 Vitali atoms:
      cв‚ѓ=1, scores=(0, 1, 3, 3, 3): 40 tournaments
      cв‚ѓ=1, scores=(0, 2, 2, 2, 4): 40 tournaments
      cв‚ѓ=1, scores=(1, 1, 1, 3, 4): 40 tournaments
    H=5: 2 Vitali atoms:
      cв‚ѓ=2, scores=(0, 2, 2, 3, 3): 120 tournaments
      cв‚ѓ=2, scores=(1, 1, 2, 2, 4): 120 tournaments
    H=15: 2 Vitali atoms:
      cв‚ѓ=4, scores=(1, 2, 2, 2, 3): 40 tournaments
      cв‚ѓ=5, scores=(2, 2, 2, 2, 2): 24 tournaments

======================================================================
PART 10: THE ABSTRACT EQUATION вЂ” FIVE FORCES, ONE IDENTITY
======================================================================

  We now zoom fully out. The five constants (e, i, ПЂ, 1, 0) represent
  five FORCES in mathematics:

  e вЂ” GROWTH (analysis, asymptotics, EGF)
  i вЂ” ROTATION (algebra, complex structure, sign)
  ПЂ вЂ” CLOSURE (geometry, periodicity, circle)
  1 вЂ” IDENTITY (category theory, unit object, terminal)
  0 вЂ” VOID (topology, nullity, initial object)

  Euler's identity says: GROWTH^{ROTATION Г— CLOSURE} + IDENTITY = VOID.
  Equivalently: GROWTH composed with ROTATION and CLOSURE, plus
  the trivial IDENTITY, gives NOTHING.

  In tournament theory:
  - GROWTH = the exponential scaling of H with n (Stirling)
  - ROTATION = the signed permanent S, the imaginary component
  - CLOSURE = RГ©dei's theorem (every tournament has a HP вЂ” completeness)
  - IDENTITY = the evaluation at x=2 (I(О©,2) = H)
  - VOID = the universal vanishings (ОІв‚‚=0, H mod 2 = 1, Walsh zeros)

  The TOURNAMENT EULER IDENTITY:
    "The exponential growth of path counting, rotated by the sign
     character and closed by RГ©dei's completeness theorem, when
     combined with the identity evaluation at 2, produces exactly
     the constraints that force all tournaments to obey H = I(О©,2)."

  This is not a formula вЂ” it is a STRUCTURAL EQUATION.
  It says: OCF is the tournament-theoretic Euler identity.

  в•”в•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•—
  в•‘  e^{iПЂ} + 1 = 0   в†”   H(T) = I(О©(T), 2)              в•‘
  в•‘                                                           в•‘
  в•‘  Both say: the five fundamental forces of mathematics,    в•‘
  в•‘  when composed correctly, produce an identity.            в•‘
  в•‘  Both are TAUTOLOGIES that reveal deep structure.         в•‘
  в•‘  Both connect analysis, algebra, geometry, combinatorics. в•‘
  в•љв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ђв•ќ


